Introduction to K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)

The training session began with an introduction to K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN), a simple yet powerful supervised Machine Learning algorithm used for both classification and regression problems. Learned that KNN is a lazy learning algorithm, meaning it does not build a model during training but instead stores the training data and makes predictions when new data is provided.

The trainer explained that KNN predicts the class of a new data point by finding the K nearest neighbors based on distance and assigning the majority class among those neighbors.

Discussed several real-world applications of KNN, including recommendation systems, medical diagnosis, handwriting recognition, image classification, and customer segmentation.

Working Principle of KNN

Studied the step-by-step working process of the KNN algorithm.

Learned that the algorithm follows these steps:

Store the training dataset.
Select the value of K (number of nearest neighbors).
Calculate the distance between the new data point and all training samples.
Identify the K closest neighbors.
Perform majority voting for classification or calculate the average for regression.
Predict the final output.

Understood that KNN makes predictions based on similarity between data points.

Choosing the Value of K

Received a detailed explanation of the importance of selecting the appropriate K value.

Learned that:

A small K value may lead to overfitting and sensitivity to noise.
A large K value may lead to underfitting and reduced accuracy.

Discussed methods for selecting the optimal K value through experimentation and model evaluation.

Practiced comparing model performance using different values such as K = 3, 5, 7, and 9.

Distance Metrics

Studied different methods used to calculate the distance between data points.

Learned about:

Euclidean Distance
Measures the straight-line distance between two points.
Most commonly used in KNN classification.
Manhattan Distance
Measures the distance by moving along horizontal and vertical paths.
Useful for grid-based datasets.
Minkowski Distance
A generalized distance metric that includes Euclidean and Manhattan distances as special cases.

Discussed how the choice of distance metric influences model performance.

